{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"99224be5-b995-4dc9-973c-531b0841a07c","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01XzFMG4QGpgvHiz365DTuvd","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Checking MSTest version"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01PkvcY1Goog79EosNWkBaPL","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-b82c0ea27ea248d28950c1ec640c9b20/TestProject.csproj"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-b82c0ea27ea248d28950c1ec640c9b20/TestProject.csproj."}],"interactionId":"b88e55a2-501d-4090-b645-2f4e14a07d4b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modern MSTest patterns for test class initialization, specifically about synchronous and asynchronous initialization, and TestContext injection. Let me provide a concise, accurate answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v3/v4.\n\nIn modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended patterns are:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use constructor injection (`TestContext` as a constructor parameter) rather than the legacy static property pattern.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use the constructor for sync init.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[ClassInitialize]` and `[TestInitialize]` for async setup, as constructors can't be async.\n\n\nI should check what version of MSTest they're working with to give them the most relevant guidance.","outputTokens":301,"requestId":"1BC1:23CF76:232C0A0:26D8D2F:6A03D77F"},"id":"58b77179-acd7-4003-9727-425477b2a44c","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:44:39.898Z","parentId":"8c3bb5ee-1256-404e-b434-c4260f2f503b"}
